No, CMD is what you have on Windows. Unfortunately, Windows isn't standard in the world of software engineering.  The type of command line app we're using is called "Bash" and can only be accessed on Linux.  However, Windows and MacOS have a way to make Bash available for you even though they're not Linux operating systems.  On Mac, your default terminal (or command line app) already runs bash.  On Windows, you can download WSL which is basically a software that allows you to run a Linux environment on your Windows computer, from which you can access Bash.  If you already use Linux, then you don't need to do anything. Bash is native to Linux and is already your default terminal (o command line app).

*Hello Team. I hope this message meets you well*  I am Bright from Bwave ICT. A peer from a previous cohort who priorities learning over anything.  The aim of this group is to provide support, peer learning, and connection between members here.  When I first started my Alx journey, I had no idea how to locate members from the previous cohorts. I didn't have anyone to ask questions, so among us, I decided to create a peer group and together, by ourselves we learnt as a team without guide from anyone. *However learning on my own without any guidance from a higher up, i made many mistakes, there were many things i wished we had known then, and in some instances, I dearly paid for my  ignorance. Eventually, I got needed help, and the help I received when I was just starting has helped me till now.*  In the same way, I have made it to help others till date, both in my cohort and in the subsequent ones.  _So I created this group for cohort 10 members to learn, connect, and get the necessary guidance to go about daily tasks and projects in alx_  *Without guide, this program will feel so difficult and confusing, as many people have different ways to do things, and some like to over complicate simple issues. That is why I want to kindly hold hands with you, and support in any way I can.*  However, I do not support copy and paste answers, sharing codes without explanation, and random spamming of the group with irrelevant links, or links to other petty groups. Remember too much of information can lead to confusion. I advise you only watch out for relevant information.   I'm a nice person 🤠, I like to play and I don't like being too serious 😂, I also want my friends and my group to be jovial and fun filled, so please let's make this group a nice place to be, a conducive environment for learning, and ease out stress. *No one is an island of knowledge, so please let's no-one feel like a boss or feel better than others because he/she has a little more experience. We are all here to learn 🤗🤗*   Daily, I'll be dropping relevant videos and explanation to projects so as to get you started during the onboarding week.  *A common mistake many people have made was to rush. They rush everything, and at the end become so overwhelmed and leave the program 🤦🏻‍♀️. As for me, I'll advise you to relax 😃. You will not miss anything by following the framework of alx. You will not loose anything by following my advice to be calm and go step by step.*  _I've helped lot's of people from cohort 8, cohort 9 and I look forward to helping cohort 10 have a blissful time here, because tomorrow, we all would be a great software engineers and partners._   Once again welcome 🤗.  If you have questions, you are always free to ask, if you want me to specially answer you, tag me @bwave , otherwise anyone who knows it in the group will answer you, or whenever I'm available, I'll be sure to answer.

When you use echo to create file contents from terminal, there is one character responsible for it. Follow this guide.  *echo "content to file" > filename* The first line you put in a text file can use the single greater than ( > ) sign. If you want to put another line after the first, you have to use double greater than ( >> ) sign. If you use the same single ( > ) to input subsequent lines, the previous ones will be overwritten with the new content.  Example: I want to write two lines of text in a file called *filename*, this is the way to go.  echo "This is first line">filename echo "This is second line">filename  If you *cat filename*, it will give you: This is first line This is second line

There is time for first dealine, if you do not meet up, then u still have secondline to try and catch up and if you still don't, then you have the third deadline.  If you finish before 1st dealine, you get 100% of your actualscore. If you finish after the first deadline but before 2nd dealine, u get only 65% of your score. If u exceed second deadline, u score only 50%. If you exceed, third deadline, I am guessing that's a 0%  Now of course, that means, if you complete the task after first deadline, you will get 100% for completion but then that will now be multiplied by 65% because u finished late. The 100% we see on the summary page is simply to tell that we have finished the task. It doesn't necessarily mean u earned 100%.  As a matter of fact, questions that involve our peers awarding us marks are even more tricky. You would get 100% for completing task and 100% for finishing before first deadline. But imagine it was marked over 5points and somebody scored you 3/5... your actual mark will be = 100%(for completing task) × 100%(for fininishing within first deadline) × (3/5) point(what your fellow peer scored you) = 3/5(60% final score)  What if you finished after first deadline before second deadline? Well, you will score, 100%  × 65% × (3/5) = 1.95/5 (35% final)   So we must be careful about how we score people.  1. Never forget to move the slider and award appropriate marks for someone's work.  2. I hate to say this but be more deliberate about who reviews your work. I am finding out that some people are careless in awarding marks or (to be less strict), don't really yet understand what they are doing.  We are responsible for our scores ooh...  Then of course they are tasks that are not review tasks, those ones the checker awards you marks based on how well the check went. But those are not the problem because the checker will inform you if you got it wrong. Your score will be affected only if you ignored the fail warning.

For the C -Hello world task  First go to github and create the repository "alx-low_level_programming" Go to your Sandbox and clone into the repo After clonning cd into the repo  Create a Readme file Add and push to git Make a new directory called "0x00-hello_world" Cd into the dir Create a Readme file Add and push to git.. Now you'd do ur tasks 0-8 under it  Task 0 Vi 0-preprocessor Enter these lines #!/bin/bash gcc -E $CFILE -o c Save and quit  Task 1 Vi 1-compiler  #!/bin/bash gcc -c $CFILE $FILE  Task 2 Vi 2-assembler  #!/bin/bash gcc -S $CFILE  Task 3 Vi 3-name  #!/bin/bash gcc $CFILE  -o cisfun  Task 4(for this task and the down to 7 u no longer need the shebang) Vi 4-puts.c Type in the following lines of code  #include <stdio.h> /** *main- Serves as the entry point for the program * *Return: By default returns zero if no erros otherwise returns non-zero value. */ int main(void) { puts(""Programming is like building a multilingual puzzle"); return (0); }  Task 5 Vi 5-printf.c  #include <stdio.h> /** * main-entry point for the program. * * Return:0 if no errors, return non zero if errors */ int main(void) { printf("with proper grammar, but the outcome is a piece of art,
"); return (0); }  Task 6 Vi 6-size.c  #include <stdio.h> /** *main -is the entry point for the program. * *Return:zero if no error, Non-zero value  if errors. */ int main(void) { printf("Size of a char: %ld byte(s)
", sizeof(char)); printf("Size of an int: %ld byte(s)
", sizeof(int)); printf("Size of a long int: %ld byte(s)
", sizeof(long int)); printf("Size of a long long int: %ld byte(s)
", sizeof(long long int)); printf("Size of a float: %ld byte(s)
", sizeof(float)); return (0); }  Task 7 Vi 100-intel  #!/bin/bash gcc -S -masm=intel $CFILE  Task 8 Vi 101-quote.c  #include <unistd.h> /** *main-program entry point. * *Return: 1 on success. */ int main(void) { write(2, "and that piece of art is useful" - Dora Korpar, 2015-10-19
", 59); return (1); }  Save and quit.. Then add all the files and push to github..  Note:. Please go through the materials given for the task; u need to understand a bit of coding else no one would understand   ur question nor be able to help. C- 0x03-Debugging..  So far you've been writing codes and encountering errors one way or the another and you've been fixing them.. that's just debugging..   So for this task You have been given codes that one thing or the other is preventing it from working so you're expected to find out what it is and fix it..  The main.h file for the tasks are given in the example box above the task.. for task 0 all you're to do is to create a main.c file and the main.h file whose content has been given..  Task 0 -create a main.h file with the content below  #ifndef MAIN_H #define MAIN_H  #include <stdio.h>  void positive_or_negative(int i); int largest_number(int a, int b, int c); int convert_day(int month, int day); void print_remaining_days(int month, int day, int year);  #endif /* MAIN.H */  -create a 0-main.c file with the content below..  #include "main.h"  /** * main - tests function that prints if integer is positive or negative * Return: 0 */  int main(void) { int i;  i = 0; positive_or_negative(i);  return (0); }  That's all u need for task 0.. Note: the prototypes for task1-3 has already been included in the main.h file above no need to include them again..  Task 1 For this you've been given a file named 1-main.c They said you should comment out the part making it an infinite loop..  If u look closely at the code I as been assigned value 0 a d it says while i<10 it should print something.. This will always be true since the value of I was incremented (I++) T So all u need to do is to turn that part of the code into a comment(it could be block comment /** **/ or line comment /*  */) Here's how ur code should look  -create a file 1-main.c with the following  #include <stdio.h>  /** * main - causes an infinite loop * Return: 0 */  int main(void) { int i;  printf("Infinite loop incoming :(
");  i = 0;  /*while (i < 10)*/ /*{*/ /*putchar(i);*/ /*}*/  printf("Infinite loop avoided! \o/
");  return (0); }  Task 2  For this you've been given a code that's not giving the correct output I believe some of us can attempt this one ourselves.. U just have to modify the statements to get the correct output.. this should work  -create a file 2-largest_number.c  #include "main.h"  /** * largest_number - returns the largest of 3 numbers * @a: first integer * @b: second integer * @c: third integer * Return: largest number */  int largest_number(int a, int b, int c) { int largest;  if (a >= b && a >= c) { largest = a; } else if (b >= a && b >= c) { largest = b; } else { largest = c; }  return (largest); }   Task 3  This is a bit technical most of us who aren't that great in maths would definitely have a hard time figuring it out They gave a code that outputs number of days remaining in a year but it doesn't output correctly in a leap year. For this u first need to know how frequent does leap year occur(4yrs) How many days In a leap year(366) With those 2 details and an understanding of using modulus operator you're all good..  This is one way to solve it.. You can though crack ur brain to come up with a different way..  -create a file  3-print_remaining_days.c  #include <stdio.h> #include "main.h"  /** * print_remaining_days - takes a date and prints how many days are * left in the year, taking leap years into account * @month: month in number format * @day: day of month * @year: year * * Return: void */  void print_remaining_days(int month, int day, int year) { if (year % 4 == 0 || ((year % 100 == 0) && (year % 400 == 0))) { if (month > 2 && day >= 60) { day++; }  printf("Day of the year: %d
", day); printf("Remaining days: %d
", 366 - day); } else { if (month == 2 && day == 60) { printf("Invalid date: %02d/%02d/%04d
", month, day - 31, year); } else { printf("Day of the year: %d
", day); printf("Remaining days: %d
", 365 - day); } } }    ... Always run ur code with Betty to see you have no issues with her And also compile the codes following the method specified on the task to ensure ur code compiles and brings out a correct output   Goodluck..  #ElFaruq😎

0x09. C Static libraries Task 0 This is the step by step process for the solving the static library project! 1. Create the 0x09... Folder and put a non empty README.md file in it. You can git push this before continuation.  2. Go to your alx-low_level_programming directory/  then paste  cp -r 0x02-functions_nested_loops/3-islower.c 0x02-functions_nested_loops/4-isalpha.c 0x02-functions_nested_loops/6-abs.c 0x04-more_functions_nested_loops/0-isupper.c 0x04-more_functions_nested_loops/1-isdigit.c 0x05-pointers_arrays_strings/2-strlen.c 0x05-pointers_arrays_strings/3-puts.c 0x05-pointers_arrays_strings/9-strcpy.c 0x05-pointers_arrays_strings/100-atoi.c 0x06-pointers_arrays_strings/0-strcat.c 0x06-pointers_arrays_strings/1-strncat.c 0x06-pointers_arrays_strings/2-strncpy.c 0x06-pointers_arrays_strings/3-strcmp.c 0x07-pointers_arrays_strings/_putchar.c 0x07-pointers_arrays_strings/0-memset.c 0x07-pointers_arrays_strings/1-memcpy.c 0x07-pointers_arrays_strings/2-strchr.c 0x07-pointers_arrays_strings/3-strspn.c 0x07-pointers_arrays_strings/4-strpbrk.c 0x07-pointers_arrays_strings/5-strstr.c 0x09-static_libraries  this will copy all the needed files all at once (20 in total actually)  3. Create a main.h file that contains the prototype of all this functions. your main.h file should be  #ifndef MAIN_H #define MAIN_H int _putchar(char c); int _islower(int c); int _isalpha(int c); int _abs(int n); int _isupper(int c); int _isdigit(int c); int _strlen(char *s); void _puts(char *s); char *_strcpy(char *dest, char *src); int _atoi(char *s); char *_strcat(char *dest, char *src); char *_strncat(char *dest, char *src, int n); char *_strncpy(char *dest, char *src, int n); int _strcmp(char *s1, char *s2); char *_memset(char *s, char b, unsigned int n); char *_memcpy(char *dest, char *src, unsigned int n); char *_strchr(char *s, char c); unsigned int _strspn(char *s, char *accept); char *_strpbrk(char *s, char *accept); char *_strstr(char *haystack, char *needle); #endif  4. Now, You can start the creation of your static library First  gcc -c *.c  (This will create a .o file from all the .c files)  Then to archive do ar -rc libmy.a *.o  Then to index do ranlib libmy.a  To confirm  ar -t libmy.a  You should have 20 .o files as shown below  __________________________________  0-isupper.o 0-memset.o 0-strcat.o 100-atoi.o 1-isdigit.o 1-memcpy.o 1-strncat.o 2-strchr.o 2-strlen.o 2-strncpy.o 3-islower.o 3-puts.o 3-strcmp.o 3-strspn.o 4-isalpha.o 4-strpbrk.o 5-strstr.o 6-abs.o 9-strcpy.o _putchar.o  __________________________  5. To Push only your libmy.a and main.h Create a .gitignore file  e.g vi .gitignore then add these 2 lines  *.c *.o  6. git add . 7. git commit -m "insert your commit message" 8. git push  9. Check your codes, it shouls all check out.

*0x09. C Static libraries* This is the step by step process for the solving the static library project! 1. Create the 0x09... Folder and put a non empty README.md file in it. You can git push this before continuation.  2. Go to your alx-low_level_programming directory/  then paste  cp -r 0x02-functions_nested_loops/3-islower.c 0x02-functions_nested_loops/4-isalpha.c 0x02-functions_nested_loops/6-abs.c 0x04-more_functions_nested_loops/0-isupper.c 0x04-more_functions_nested_loops/1-isdigit.c 0x05-pointers_arrays_strings/2-strlen.c 0x05-pointers_arrays_strings/3-puts.c 0x05-pointers_arrays_strings/9-strcpy.c 0x05-pointers_arrays_strings/100-atoi.c 0x06-pointers_arrays_strings/0-strcat.c 0x06-pointers_arrays_strings/1-strncat.c 0x06-pointers_arrays_strings/2-strncpy.c 0x06-pointers_arrays_strings/3-strcmp.c 0x06-pointers_arrays_strings/_putchar.c 0x07-pointers_arrays_strings/0-memset.c 0x07-pointers_arrays_strings/1-memcpy.c 0x07-pointers_arrays_strings/2-strchr.c 0x07-pointers_arrays_strings/3-strspn.c 0x07-pointers_arrays_strings/4-strpbrk.c 0x07-pointers_arrays_strings/5-strstr.c 0x09-static_libraries  this will copy all the needed files all at once (20 in total actually)  3. Create a main.h file that contains the prototype of all this functions. your main.h file should be  #ifndef MAIN_H #define MAIN_H int _putchar(char c); int _islower(int c); int _isalpha(int c); int _abs(int n); int _isupper(int c); int _isdigit(int c); int _strlen(char *s); void _puts(char *s); char *_strcpy(char *dest, char *src); int _atoi(char *s); char *_strcat(char *dest, char *src); char *_strncat(char *dest, char *src, int n); char *_strncpy(char *dest, char *src, int n); int _strcmp(char *s1, char *s2); char *_memset(char *s, char b, unsigned int n); char *_memcpy(char *dest, char *src, unsigned int n); char *_strchr(char *s, char c); unsigned int _strspn(char *s, char *accept); char *_strpbrk(char *s, char *accept); char *_strstr(char *haystack, char *needle); #endif  4. Now, You can start the creation of your static library First  gcc -c *.c  (This will create a .o file from all the .c files)  Then to archive do ar -rc libmy.a *.o  Then to index do ranlib libmy.a  To confirm  ar -t libmy.a  You should have 20 .o files as shown below  __________________________________  0-isupper.o 0-memset.o 0-strcat.o 100-atoi.o 1-isdigit.o 1-memcpy.o 1-strncat.o 2-strchr.o 2-strlen.o 2-strncpy.o 3-islower.o 3-puts.o 3-strcmp.o 3-strspn.o 4-isalpha.o 4-strpbrk.o 5-strstr.o 6-abs.o 9-strcpy.o _putchar.o  __________________________  5. To Push only your libmy.a and main.h Create a .gitignore file  e.g vi .gitignore then add these 2 lines  *.c *.o  6. git add . 7. git commit -m "insert your commit message" 8. git push  9. Check your codes, it shouls all check out.

*How you can remember what you are learning.*  *Somebody asked me “How can I memorize all these codes?”*  Below are my proven strategies to remember and move ahead on my coding and programming journey. I know it will help someone here.....Read on  1.*Focus on concepts and ideas:* We don’t learn human languages from just a dictionary alone. Instead, we want to put our skills and ability by working on projects. Don’t focus on remembering code, remember ideas. By understanding underlying concepts and algorithms, you will be able to code in multiple languages. if you meet those that code, most times, they run to google to get the syntax of a particular code but the concepts and algorithms remain with them forever. Therefore, focus on learning key languages and concepts instead of clamming the codes.   *2.Apply what you are learning through working on projects:* You can start from simple projects and progress into more complex projects. As you practice on the projects, the knowledge gained through knowing the concepts begins to cement on your medulla without you having to cram them.   *3.View other people’s projects and code base:*  Search GitHub for other people’s code base and begin to collaborate with others on git. As you keep doing that you will begin to see how others code and you learn in the process.   *4.Find a community to share, collaborate, give, and receive feedback on projects:* Dribble, be and GitHub is my favorite places to collaborate and even social media pages.   *5.Be open to good and bad feedback and provide feedback to others:*  Be humble to learn from others. Don’t get annoyed when someone gives you negative feedback on your projects. learn and keep moving ahead.   *6. Know where to find the answers to your questions:* compile good resources, Good websites, blogs, and youtube videos, These tools will serve as your go go-traces when you run into problems and challenges.  *7.Take Notes:*  Note-taking helps you solidify your learning as you go through your materials. There is something very important with note-taking time. A lot of people watch videos and they don’t remember a thing after a whole course of the video simply because they don’t commit themselves to take notes  *8.PRACTICE! PRACTICE!! PRACTICE!!!* If you can set out at least 5hrs a day to coding and practice, you will be surprised on at how far you will go after a short period of time  *Practical Advice from Megagig solutions. Join us on twitter on the handle @megagigsolution*

some reviews about C programming

You might be able to get a job without learning a fundemental language like C, but you won't get much further, and you'll find things a lot more confusing. C is the basis of almost all modern languages today. Learn it, and everything else will make sense. You don't need to learn everythingy about it, or even become proficient in it, but just have a basic understanding of it.

I think every programmer should learn C, C++ and move from there to other languages. I dont think anyone should call himself/herself as software engineer if they dont know these languages. Actually of course software engineers know these languages. Its primary languages in all universities around world in software engineering departments. Self learners or attendars of bootcamps may skip them, but if they want to be better in this area , better they start learning C and C++. Its not waste of time.
C will be never replaced. As close you are to hardware the faster you are. God damn Java won't provide you that.
If you want to learn how a computer works, learn C. If you want to get a job, learn Python/JavaScript

Majority of microcontrollers are still coded in C. So whether or not its considered obsolete in the realm of software, it most definitely isnt in general, simply because just about every electronic has firmware or an embedded system with a microcontroller running C on it

In my experience, you still have to do the work.  It doesn't matter what language you write in above assembler, you still need to wire everything up and make it work.  Java and C++ may allow some more expressive idioms but in general, they are doing the same work and only tend to hide the complexity which causes issues in maintenance.  I saw that a lot when trying to unpack some of the newer architecture patterns like dependency injection, etc.

In my worthless opinion, C, as well as assembler, are the main languages for embedded processor programming. To write code that actually follows what is going on inside the processor may be more difficult and time consuming, but it is infinitely more rewarding than pushing around program lines that are transparent to the CPU. I don't have a religious affiliation with any particular program language. But C and Assembly make you a better programmer  for higher level languages. When you understand how the CPU recognizes 1s and 0s and how its particular structure converts these bits into information and output control, you can visualize what your lines of code are actually doing. This, for me at least, allows me to have a much better understanding of what each line of code actually means. Therefore I make fewer mistakes and can solve programming problems much faster, no matter what program language I am using.
